body:
Steve Rogers under different directors

Joe Johnston: Established who Steve Rogers is as a person. Emphasized that “Captain America” is just a title and what truly makes Steve a hero is his good heart and bravery. Also emphasized Steve’s social awkwardness, especially around women.

Joss Whedon: Lol, Steve is an old man. He’s from the forties so he’s like a grandpa.

Alan Taylor: It’s actually Loki but still, he let Chris Evans fuck around on set, so there’s that.

The Russo Brothers: Going from Joe Johnston’s example, they grew Steve as a character by emphasizing his loneliness and depression as a result of him being in a time period he doesn’t belong in. Also, they focused more on Steve’s Captain America side than his Steve side (the superhero vs the man). He’s a lot more comfortable with being “Captain America” in comparison to First Avenger. Lastly…Bucky. Lots and lots of Bucky love.

Jon Watts: Instructional video guide for high schoolers

description:
Steve Rogers surprises his teammate-turned friend-turned girlfriend with a date under the stars, when she thinks they are going to Tony Stark’s housewarming party. No swearing, no sex, or alcohol involved. Very sweet fluff, may cause squealing and/or gazing dreamily into the distance. Mentions Phil, Tony, Pepper, etc. Written before seeing CA:CW.  


Reposting this because I thought people might want some Happy-Steve time before ENGAME comes out. I know I need some Happy-Steve before we see him dealing with his grief over Bucky & co.
